        "name": "An Optimized End-to-End Quantum Compilation and Execution Pipeline for Simulations",     affiliation: "IEEE Canadian Students and Young Professionals (CSYP) Conference 2025",     link: "https://www.researchgate.net/publication/395415715_An_Optimized_End-to-End_Quantum_Compilation_and_Execution_Pipeline_for_Simulations",     linkName: "Poster",     description: `We hypothesize that an improved optimum of performance and vertical stack integration could be achieved by re-designing components of the quantum computing stack, focusing on the compilation and execution of simulations. This yields designs and implementations of new compiler frontend technologies, centered on a JSON based intermediate representation, JQIR, inspired by MLIR and QIR. Our framework is implemented in TypeScript and centred on JQIR for web compatibility. This produces a compilation target that is easily consumable by web APIs. Lexing, parsing and compiling can be achieved entirely in the front-end. We find that while providing better integration with web APIs, this technology performs more optimally than IBMs ANTLR parser by an average of over 7ms when compared across multiple quantum algorithms written in QASM 3.0, and it supports more language features than the experimental Rust parser. The pipeline for our Q# dialect also performs comparably to Microsofts (7.60ms vs. Microsofts 7.29ms for Grover.qs). After a program is compiled, it must be executed by a backend. We aim to improve on emulators, including analog emulators like La Cour and Otts, as well as FPGA-based digital emulators like Jakub and Dlugopolskis. In terms of execution, we propose a novel VLIW hybrid analog / digital processor architecture, optimized for performing the simulation of quantum algorithms. The instruction set architecture makes quantum gates first-class citizens, making the dispatch of operations from the IR straightforward. We assess the performance of the architecture and find that it should perform comparably (slightly better in some cases) to other emulators previously proposed in the literature.`
